	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f104217191236535><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj>battle tactics</span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=26755><span id=Scholar>nimbledigits</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>59 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Jan 9th 11:39 PM 2003</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.26]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I have a real noob of a question here, but please bear with me.<br> <br>My main is a 20th level rogue whom I have almost exclusively soloed (I know we are not soloists, but I can be a bit thickheaded and wanted to find out for myself).&nbsp;&nbsp;While I enjoy roleplaying the solitary rogue and have done pretty well for myself, I am finding it more and more difficult to advance, and am inclined to start grouping.  <br> <br>My battle plan to now has consisted of sneaking up on some one, hopefully landing that first backstab, and then auto-attacking, using backstab as an additional frontal attack or spell interrupter when necessary.  Of course, I also pickpocket the mob a few times, so if I have to retreat, at least I've got a little something to ease the pain.  As a result, I have no experience with the tactics of online rpg group battle, so here goes...<br> <br>When in battle, should I stand back from the fray and ONLY step in to backstab, or should I auto-attack and just backstab when the situation presents itself, or should I do something in between?  I don't want to draw all the aggro, but I also want to pull my weight. I realize the tactics will vary to suit a particular situation and there will not be a cut-&amp;-dried answer, but I'd appreciate any thoughts.<br>  <br>Thank you,<br>&nbsp;<br>Nimbledigits Throatslitter<br>Leatherfoot Raider of the 20th Shadow<br>Mith Marr</td></tr>
