	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Jan 11th 2:19 AM 2003</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>at lower levels, a rogue is only as good as the tank that can keep aggro.&nbsp;&nbsp;Unless the person is nicely equip, you will get aggro fairly often even if you had sub-par gear.  This is both a good and bad thing.  You want to get hit every so often to bring up your defense, which also brings up your AC.  Higher AC = more mob misses and for lower damage when it does hit.  It's not good for the mob to constantly be facing you because you won't be able to backstab as often plus the mob will riposte/parry/dodge your attacks.  At lower levels the ripostes don't hurt as much, but once the mobs become stronger, ripostes do some heavy damage.  When you attack from behind, the mob cannot dodge/riposte/parry so more of your attacks land :)<br><br>Use your f2/f3/f4/f5/f6 keys to target group members.  If the tank is in the f2 slot, hit that after each fight so he's targeted.  Make a hotkey, first line /G Assisting [ %T ] then second line /Assist   This lets your group know you're assisting the main tank and not hitting random mob01.  Let the tank hit the mob for 2-3 seconds then jump in with attack, then BS.  If the mob turns on you, use your evade key or turn off attack then hide if you do it manually.  If you keep stealing aggro, either take a few hits while you keep swinging or stop attacking and let the tank get aggro back.<br>&nbsp;<br>Derrict - Nameless<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=362635" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=362635</a></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
